            <p className="text-sm text-slate-500 italic">Photo by RDNE Stock project from Pexels</p>
          </header>

          <div className="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
            <p>Falls are a major concern for seniors, potentially leading to serious injuries and decreased independence. This comprehensive guide provides practical strategies to create a safer home environment and reduce the risk of falls.</p>

            <h2>Understanding Fall Risks</h2>
            <p>As we age, various factors can increase the risk of falls:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Decreased balance and muscle strength</li>
              <li>Vision problems</li>
              <li>Medication side effects</li>
              <li>Chronic health conditions</li>
              <li>Environmental hazards</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Home Safety Modifications</h2>
            <p>Making these simple changes can significantly reduce fall risks:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Install handrails on both sides of stairs</li>
              <li>Add grab bars in bathrooms near toilets and in showers</li>
              <li>Ensure adequate lighting throughout the home</li>
              <li>Remove or secure loose rugs</li>
              <li>Keep frequently used items within easy reach</li>
              <li>Maintain clear pathways through rooms</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Exercise and Physical Activity</h2>
            <p>Regular exercise helps maintain:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Balance and coordination</li>
              <li>Muscle strength</li>
              <li>Bone density</li>
              <li>Overall mobility</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Recommended exercises (always consult healthcare providers before starting new exercise routines):</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Tai Chi</li>
              <li>Balance exercises</li>
              <li>Gentle strength training</li>
              <li>Walking with proper assistance if needed</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Regular Health Check-ups</h2>
            <p>Maintain regular appointments for:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Vision checks</li>
              <li>Medication reviews</li>
              <li>Balance assessments</li>
              <li>General health monitoring</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Additional Safety Tips</h2>
            <ul>
              <li>Wear properly fitting, non-slip footwear</li>
              <li>Use assistive devices when recommended</li>
              <li>Stay hydrated and maintain good nutrition</li>
              <li>Be aware of medication side effects</li>
              <li>Keep emergency contact information readily available</li>
            </ul>

            <div className="bg-primary/5 p-6 rounded-xl mt-8">
              <h3>Professional Assessment</h3>
              <p>Consider having an occupational therapist or certified aging-in-place specialist evaluate your home for additional safety recommendations specific to your situation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
